I will have a lengthy analysis of Warren Buffett and Berkshire Hathaway tomorrow morning on @realmoney There was a lot spoken and unpsoken from yesterday's near five hour marathon that needs to be discussed. There were a lot of important business/investment themes and life

lessons delivered by Warren. Over the years I have been of the view that Berkshire is a GDP/S&P like stock and a victim of its enormous successes - the company is simply too large to succeed (relatively speaking) from both a profit and market standpoint.

The returns since I appeared in Omaha in 2013 support my view. Berkshire is now a "stay rich" investment and not a "get rich" investment But, I find it laughable that the many anonymous Twitter critics of Buffett (in the cheap seats or in their parents' basements),

critical of his recent results and even of value investing -- are fatuous, dogmatic in view (naturally favoring their own "incomparable" approach), non rigorous in their criticism (they rarely mention the oddlot $70 billion he has accumulated) and are envious or feel a need to
